SIMPLE: precipitant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precipitant
<hw>Pre*cip"i*tant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praecipitans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>praecipitare</ets>: cf. F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧cipitant</ets>. See
<er>Precipitate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Falling or rushing
headlong; rushing swiftly, violently, or recklessly; moving
precipitately.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They leave their little lives⟦br⟧
Above the clouds, <qex>precipitant</qex> to earth.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Should he return, that troop so blithe and bold,⟦br⟧
<qex>Precipitant</qex> in fear would wing their flight.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unexpectedly or foolishly brought on or hastened;
rashly hurried; hasty; sudden; reckless.</def> <au>Jer. Taylor.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Precipitant</xex> rebellion.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Eikon
Basilike.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precipitant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Precipitant
<hw>Pre*cip"i*tant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any force
or reagent which causes the formation of a precipitate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precipitantly</ent>⟦br⟧
